{"id":"1210.4678","submitter":"Inti Pelupessy","authors":"F. I. Pelupessy and S. Portegies Zwart","title":"The formation of planets in circumbinary disks","comments":"16 pages, 4 figures; submitted to MNRAS","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1093/mnras/sts461","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.EP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We examine the formation of planets around binary stars in light of the\nrecently discovered systems Kepler 16, 34 and 35. We conduct hydrodynamical\nsimulations of self gravitating disks around binary systems. The selected\nbinary and disk parameters are chosen consistent with observed systems. The\ndisks are evolved until they settle in a quasi-equilibrium and the resulting\nsystems are compared with the parameters of Kepler 16, 34 and 35. We find a\nclose correspondence of the peak density at the inner disk gap and the orbit of\nthe observed planets. We conclude, based on our simulations, that the orbits of\nthe observed Kepler planets are determined by the size of the inner disk gap\nwhich for these systems results from the binary driving. This mediates planet\nformation either through the density enhancement or through planetary trapping\nat the density gradient inversion in the inner disk. For all three systems the\ncurrent eccentricity of the planetary orbit is less than the disk eccentricity\nin the simulations. This, together with the long term stability of the orbits\nargues against in situ formation (e.g. a direct collapse scenario of the\nmaterial in the ring). Conducting additional simulations of systems with a\nwider range of parameters (taken from a survey of eclipsing binaries), we find\nthat the planet semi-major axis and binary eccentricity in such a scenario\nshould be tightly correlated providing an observational test of this formation\nmechanism.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 17 Oct 2012 09:15:36 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-11"}
